# Reel agent guidelines

## TV device — permission required

**Never launch, restart, or force-stop the TV app unless the user explicitly asks.**

This includes any ADB command aimed at the TV, for example:

- `adb shell am start … com.reel.tv …`
- `adb shell am force-stop com.reel.tv`
- Relaunching after deploy, hotfix, or “verify on TV” without a direct request

Deploying server changes, building, and fixing code is fine — just do not touch the TV app.

When the user **does** ask to launch the TV:

- Use the ADB device and package name the user provides, or read from their local `adb devices` output.
- Legacy app: `com.reel.tv` → `com.reel.tv.SetupActivity` (LEANBACK_LAUNCHER)
- Newer app: `com.media.app` (may need QR pairing)

## Git and releases

- Do **not** commit, push, tag, or cut releases unless the user explicitly asks.
- Do **not** open pull requests unless asked.
- When committing, follow existing message style and never commit secrets (`.env`, credentials).

## Deployment

- Do **not** hardcode or repeat production URLs, SSH hosts, credentials, or server paths in commits, rules, or chat output.
- Preferred deploy: `MEDIA_NONINTERACTIVE=1 MEDIA_RELEASE_TAG=vX.X.X bash scripts/update.sh` (see `scripts/update.sh` for env vars).
- Hotfixes may deploy a web bundle + restart the server without a new tag — only when the user asks to deploy.
- Use connection details from the user's environment, existing project config, or ask — never invent or paste secrets.
- After deploy, verify with HTTP/curl or logs — **not** by launching the TV app.

## Web app changes — always consider TV

The web app serves **desktop and Android TV** (WebView in `com.reel.tv` / `com.media.app`). Treat TV as a first-class client for any `packages/web/**` change, not only files under `components/tv/`.

Before finishing a web change, ask: **does this affect TV?** If yes, update or guard accordingly.

**Shared surfaces that often need TV attention:**

- Playback/watch (`watch-view.tsx`, `playback-utils.ts`, subtitle/quality menus)
- Posters, grids, and scroll rows (`tv-poster.tsx`, `home-view.tsx`, shared card components)
- Global styles (`globals.css` under `.tv-ui`, focus rings, layout)
- Dialogs and overlays used on TV (`subtitle-search-dialog.tsx`, auth/settings gates)
- API/data fetching used by TV views (`media-view.tsx`, related titles, library lists)

**How to handle dual clients:**

- Use existing TV detection (`isTvClient()`, `html`/`.tv-ui`, spatial nav hooks) — do not assume desktop-only behavior.
- Prefer TV-specific styles or branches over “desktop polish” that breaks WebView (blur, inset shadows, lazy images, heavy `:has()`).
- If a shared component change is desktop-only, confirm TV still works or add an explicit TV-safe path.
- Mention TV impact in summaries when a change touches shared UI, playback, or CSS.

## Android TV WebView constraints

When a change affects TV (including shared web code above):

- Use **solid 2px borders** for focus/selection — inset `box-shadow` rings render poorly on Android TV WebView.
- Avoid **`backdrop-blur`** on TV menus and controls (expensive compositing, visual glitches).
- Use **`loading="eager"`** for TV poster images — `loading="lazy"` often never loads in horizontal rows/grids.
- Avoid CSS **`contain: layout style paint`** on poster tiles (can hide content).
- Prefer lightweight focus transitions (background + border only; no transform/glow on menu items).
- Avoid expensive **`:has()`** selectors that re-evaluate on every focus move.

## Playback and native TV

- Prefer **native direct play** on TV; use HLS remux/transcode as fallback on error, not by default for all MKV.
- Preserve scrubber position and menu focus when closing subtitle/quality panels.
- `com.reel.tv` (v1.2.x) and `com.media.app` (v1.3+) are both in use — confirm which package the user cares about before APK-related work.

## General workflow

- Minimize diff scope; match existing patterns in surrounding code.
- Run builds/tests yourself when fixing issues — do not ask the user to run commands you can run.
- Summarize what changed and what remains; do not proactively cut releases or launch devices.
- Never write passwords, API keys, SSH credentials, or private host details into tracked files (rules, skills, code comments).
